metadata.name: Bound #97
metadata.description:
Knots bind and hold, mark time, and unite. But the power of a well-tied knot isn't only to fasten – it also symbolizes how tightly one holds their pledges. Whether a commitment to a partner, community, or oneself – the longevity of a deeply held bond is often marked with a symbol of passing time, like knots tied in a rope.

Let these ropes remind us of the binds we hold – new ones, lengthy ones, unbreakable ones, and even those we’ve had to untie. In plain view, these knots invite us to contemplate what our bonds mean to us, and to see them anew.

---

Press ‘1’-’9’ to increase resolution
Press 's' to save an image of the output at the current resolution

Created with p5.js
For third party license information, please see license.md

---

TENDER x David Brice Allen
July 2022

metadata.name: Sabler : Serengeti #52
metadata.description:
'Sabler : Serengeti' is a special edition reissue of the original Sabler generator in a vibrant 'Serengeti' palette which was omitted from the original collection. 

Towards the end of the production of the original Sabler collection, the creative decision was made to reduce the number of palettes from the thirteen that had been created to a smaller number, in order to improve the cohesiveness of the collection overall. While 'Serengeti' remained one of the stronger palettes, it was ultimately excluded in favour of the 'Annaliese' palette, in homage to an Anni Albers tapestry that originally inspired the 'Sabler' collection. 

Here, the 'Serengeti' palette is provided as a companion piece to the original Sabler collection to give collectors the opportunity to pair their output with their existing collection if they choose.

Below follows an edited description for the original 'Sabler' collection:

'Sabler', an anagram of 'Albers', is a generative homage to the work of the Bauhaus textile artist Anni Albers.

The aesthetic of this piece and its proportions are guided by the Golden Ratio (1.618 : 1) and as such, each part of the composition relates in some way to its larger self.

As lines playfully extend and overlap one another from various grid segments, patterns appear, 'ghost' shadings emerge and complexity is implied even with the use of very simple elements.

There are no rarities or special features, other than for you to enjoy the unique qualities of your piece!

You can save a high resolution 3000px x 3000px PNG of your edition by pressing the 'S' key.

metadata.name: September #249
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle “live mode”. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)
---------------
teaboswell 2022

metadata.name: Leviathan #82
metadata.description:
Leviathan is a generative collection of large bodies made form particles, materialised from the viewers own subconscious. Atoms form gargantuan objects - subatomic monoliths and microscopic giants. Playing with the sense of scale it draws on the viewer’s subjective way of associating forms, a pattern that becomes a mirror, a skeleton for them to project. 

Part artist, part viewer. Leviathan asks us to question these relationships of creation, ownership and meaning. It is a chemical reaction that the artist starts and you finish. A colossal dream we are all sharing together - a leviathan.


Controls:
s or double tap: Download image
1 : Download 2400 x 4000
2 : Download 3600 x 6000
3 : Download 4800 x 8000
4 : Download 7200 x 12000

metadata.name: Win95 Larvas #109
metadata.description:
Welcome to the Win95 Larvas 🐛

Win95 Larvas is a collaboration with DOS Larvas, a CC0 project on the Tezos Blockchain. 

The Win95 Larvas are a 24x24 px remix of the original DOS Larvas released January 28 2022 on Fx Hash, using the 16 colors available in Windows95.


🐛 Size: 24x24 pixel
🐛 Format: .png
🐛 Colors 16
🐛 Layers: 9
🐛 Traits: 17
🐛 Glitch levels: 5

* Thanks to PureSpider for the great code.

metadata.name: stranger's gift #56
metadata.description:
A human being is the most intelligent and ambiguous particle of the vast organism, for we are the only ones who, in addition to maintaining common life, have the ability to harm our world and each other. Like any particle, the individual can only be fully aware of his own existence and path.

You are surrounded by people. On the scale there are over seven billion people around you. Most of them you do not know and will never know. Just as you don't think about every drop in the sea, you don't think about the existence of each individual person. A person is not in your own world until he/she/they etc. touches it. But, just as in the current of the sea you may come across a sharp stone or the most beautiful pearl, so in the mass of people you may come across that stranger.
He is a constant variable. You can't recognize him among the faceless landscape until he stands at the edge of your world. At the same time, his figure is sacred and not accidental. You were meant to meet him, and he was meant to meet you.
The Stranger has a gift for you. He can show you what the future holds, or answer questions that have long tormented you. 
This moment is a second before you meet your personal stranger.
Where will you meet him? Will he scare you or charm you? What gift will he give you and why? What will he predict for you?
This will be your personal story. Whether you want to tell it or keep it to yourself is up to you.


Code by PureSpider
